<subSubSection pageId="40" pageNumber="41" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="40.[151,1436,1546,1930]" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,273,1546,1571]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="40" pageNumber="41" reason="1">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Specimens to 
<quantity box="[438,482,1546,1570]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="40" pageNumber="41" unit="m" value="1.0">1 m</quantity>
long in life (Fautin 
<emphasis box="[708,765,1546,1570]" italics="true" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">et al.</emphasis>
1989); preserved specimens greatly contracted (
<quantity box="[1311,1405,1546,1570]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="40" pageNumber="41" unit="mm" value="100.0">100 mm</quantity>
or less in length). Column smooth, white to pale salmon or brown. Margin typically contracted, partially or completely hiding oral disc (
<figureCitation box="[491,610,1618,1642]" captionStart="FIGURE 32" captionStartId="41.[151,250,1518,1541]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,519,1496]" captionTargetId="figure-153@41.[151,1436,519,1496]" captionTargetPageId="41" captionText="FIGURE 32. Oral view of Metridium farcimen showing stiffened lobes of oral disc (KUIZ 001436)." pageId="40" pageNumber="41">Figure 32</figureCitation>
). Oral disc with lobes thickened with mesoglea. Oral disc covered in hundreds of tentacles; marginal tentacles shorter than discal tentacles. Pedal disc typically attached to rock or shell. For a detailed description of 
<emphasis box="[473,616,1690,1714]" italics="true" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Brandt" baseAuthorityYear="1835" box="[473,612,1690,1714]" class="Anthozoa" family="Metridiidae" genus="Metridium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Actiniaria" pageId="40" pageNumber="41" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="farcimen">M. farcimen</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
see Fautin 
<emphasis box="[745,801,1690,1714]" italics="true" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">et al.</emphasis>
(1989).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="40.[151,1436,1546,1930]" box="[199,1194,1726,1751]" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,291,1726,1751]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="40" pageNumber="41" reason="1">Cnidae.</emphasis>
Spirocysts, basitrichs, microbasic 
<emphasis box="[680,694,1727,1750]" italics="true" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">p</emphasis>
-mastigophores, microbasic amastigophores.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="41" lastPageNumber="42" pageId="40" pageNumber="41" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="40.[151,1436,1546,1930]" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,352,1762,1787]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="40" pageNumber="41" reason="1">Distribution.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Brandt" baseAuthorityYear="1835" box="[360,584,1762,1786]" class="Anthozoa" family="Metridiidae" genus="Metridium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Actiniaria" pageId="40" pageNumber="41" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="farcimen">
<emphasis box="[360,584,1762,1786]" italics="true" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">Metridium farcimen</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was described by 
<bibRefCitation author="Brandt, J. F." box="[794,952,1762,1786]" pageId="40" pageNumber="41" refId="ref23308" refString="Brandt, J. F. (1835) Prodromus Descriptionis Animalium AB H. Mertensio in Orbis Terrarum Circumnavigatione Observatorum. Vol. 1. Sumptibus Academiae, Petropoli, 75 pp." type="book" year="1835">Brandt (1835)</bibRefCitation>
from 
<collectingRegion box="[1022,1152,1762,1786]" country="Russia" name="Kamchatka" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">Kamchatka</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[1164,1243,1762,1786]" name="Russia" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">Russia</collectingCountry>
. Specimens have since been collected throughout the North Pacific Ocean and we extend the range of the species from subtidal waters to 
<quantity box="[259,353,1834,1858]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.7399999999999998" pageId="40" pageNumber="41" unit="m" value="2740.0">2,740 m</quantity>
, north to the Bering Sea and within the North Pacific from 
<collectingCountry box="[1018,1103,1834,1858]" name="Mexico" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">Mexico</collectingCountry>
to 
<collectingCountry box="[1139,1214,1834,1858]" name="Russia" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">Russia</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation box="[1228,1341,1834,1858]" captionStart="FIGURE 33" captionStartId="42.[151,250,1147,1170]" captionTargetBox="[152,1434,187,1137]" captionTargetId="figure-263@42.[151,1436,185,1137]" captionTargetPageId="42" captionText="FIGURE 33. Distribution of Metridium farcimen from Mexico to Russia." pageId="40" pageNumber="41">Figure 33</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="40.[151,1436,1546,1930]" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,446,1870,1895]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="40" pageNumber="41" reason="1">Taxonomic remarks.</emphasis>
Fautin 
<emphasis box="[535,593,1870,1894]" italics="true" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">et al.</emphasis>
(1989) described as a new species 
<taxonomicName authority="Fautin, Bucklin, and Hand, 1989" authorityName="Fautin, Bucklin, and Hand" authorityYear="1989" class="Anthozoa" family="Metridiidae" genus="Metridium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Actiniaria" pageId="40" pageNumber="41" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="giganteum">
<emphasis box="[999,1244,1870,1894]" italics="true" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">Metridium giganteum</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Fautin, D. G. &amp; Bucklin, A. &amp; Hand, C." pageId="40" pageNumber="41" pagination="77 - 85" refId="ref24310" refString="Fautin, D. G., Bucklin, A. &amp; Hand, C. (1989) Systematics of sea anemones belonging to genus Metridium (Coelenterata: Actiniaria), with a description of M. giganteum new species. Wasmann Journal of Biology, 47 (1 - 2), 77 - 85." type="journal article" year="1989">Fautin, Bucklin, and Hand, 1989</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, distinguishing it from the two other species found along the northeastern Pacific coast, 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Linnaeus" baseAuthorityYear="1761" box="[1332,1436,1906,1930]" class="Anthozoa" family="Metridiidae" genus="Metridium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Actiniaria" pageId="40" pageNumber="41" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="senile">
<emphasis box="[1332,1436,1906,1930]" italics="true" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">M. senile</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="40.[151,1436,1942,2002]" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">
(
<bibRefCitation author="Linnaeus, C." box="[158,339,1942,1966]" pageId="40" pageNumber="41" refId="ref25090" refString="Linnaeus, C. (1761) Fauna Svecica. Laurentii Salvii, Stockholm, Sweden, 578 pp." type="book" year="1761">Linnaeus, 1761</bibRefCitation>
) and 
<taxonomicName authority="Hand, 1956" authorityName="Hand" authorityYear="1956" box="[412,657,1942,1966]" class="Anthozoa" family="Metridiidae" genus="Metridium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Actiniaria" pageId="40" pageNumber="41" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="exile">
<emphasis box="[412,507,1942,1966]" italics="true" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">M. exile</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Hand, C." box="[519,657,1942,1966]" pageId="40" pageNumber="41" pagination="189 - 251" refId="ref24892" refString="Hand, C. (1956, for 1955) The sea anemones of central California Part III. The acontiarian anemones. Wasmann Journal of Biology, 13 (2), 189 - 251." type="journal article" year="1956">Hand, 1956</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
. However, 
<bibRefCitation author="Fautin, D. G. &amp; Hand, C." box="[794,1077,1942,1966]" pageId="40" pageNumber="41" pagination="1151 - 1161" refId="ref24418" refString="Fautin, D. G. &amp; Hand, C. (2000) Metridium farcimen, the valid name of a common North Pacific sea anemone (Cnidaria: Actiniaria: Acontiaria). Proceedings of the Biological Society of Washington, 113 (4), 1151 - 1161." type="journal article" year="2000">Fautin and Hand (2000)</bibRefCitation>
found several names that had previously been applied to this species: its valid name is 
<taxonomicName authority="(Brandt, 1835)" baseAuthorityName="Brandt" baseAuthorityYear="1835" box="[787,1097,1978,2002]" class="Anthozoa" family="Metridiidae" genus="Metridium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Actiniaria" pageId="40" pageNumber="41" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="farcimen">
<emphasis box="[787,922,1978,2002]" italics="true" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">M. farcimen</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Brandt, J. F." box="[937,1089,1978,2002]" pageId="40" pageNumber="41" refId="ref23308" refString="Brandt, J. F. (1835) Prodromus Descriptionis Animalium AB H. Mertensio in Orbis Terrarum Circumnavigatione Observatorum. Vol. 1. Sumptibus Academiae, Petropoli, 75 pp." type="book" year="1835">Brandt, 1835</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="41.[151,1436,151,428]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">
Its great size and lobed oral disc make large specimens of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Brandt" baseAuthorityYear="1835" box="[886,1113,152,176]" class="Anthozoa" family="Metridiidae" genus="Metridium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Actiniaria" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="farcimen">
<emphasis box="[886,1113,152,176]" italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Metridium farcimen</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
among the most distinctive species of sea anemone in the North Pacific. However, small specimens of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Brandt" baseAuthorityYear="1835" box="[1008,1145,188,212]" class="Anthozoa" family="Metridiidae" genus="Metridium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Actiniaria" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="farcimen">
<emphasis box="[1008,1145,188,212]" italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">M. farcimen</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have been confused with and misidentified as 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Linnaeus" baseAuthorityYear="1761" box="[383,485,224,248]" class="Anthozoa" family="Metridiidae" genus="Metridium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Actiniaria" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="senile">
<emphasis box="[383,485,224,248]" italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">M. senile</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in publication, and because of their similarities, it is not possible to determine which were the subject of some publications (
<bibRefCitation author="Fautin, D. G. &amp; Hand, C." box="[585,821,260,284]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" pagination="1151 - 1161" refId="ref24418" refString="Fautin, D. G. &amp; Hand, C. (2000) Metridium farcimen, the valid name of a common North Pacific sea anemone (Cnidaria: Actiniaria: Acontiaria). Proceedings of the Biological Society of Washington, 113 (4), 1151 - 1161." type="journal article" year="2000">Fautin &amp; Hand 2000</bibRefCitation>
). Specimens of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Brandt" baseAuthorityYear="1835" box="[996,1131,260,284]" class="Anthozoa" family="Metridiidae" genus="Metridium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Actiniaria" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="farcimen">
<emphasis box="[996,1131,260,284]" italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">M. farcimen</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can grow much larger than specimens of 
<emphasis box="[307,417,296,320]" italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Linnaeus" baseAuthorityYear="1761" box="[307,414,296,320]" class="Anthozoa" family="Metridiidae" genus="Metridium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Actiniaria" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="senile">M. senile</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
which reach a maximum length of only 
<quantity box="[881,974,295,319]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" unit="mm" value="100.0">100 mm</quantity>
(Fautin 
<emphasis box="[1072,1129,296,320]" italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">et al.</emphasis>
1989). The oral disc of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Brandt" baseAuthorityYear="1835" class="Anthozoa" family="Metridiidae" genus="Metridium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Actiniaria" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="farcimen">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">M. farcimen</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is divided into distinct stiffened lobes whereas the oral disc of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Linnaeus" baseAuthorityYear="1761" box="[970,1074,332,356]" class="Anthozoa" family="Metridiidae" genus="Metridium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Actiniaria" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="senile">
<emphasis box="[970,1074,332,356]" italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">M. senile</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is flaccid and the lobes are less distinct.
</paragraph>
